english:
  title: Letter to the Grand Councillor of the Silver Terrace
  author: Kim Gu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    With reverence, I address this letter to Your Excellency, the Grand Councillor of the Silver Terrace. As the first day of the first month arrives, marking a new beginning, winter departs and spring approaches. I contemplate how your health flourishes in harmony, and trust you shall receive all five blessings abundantly. Since entering court and receiving your gracious correspondence, I have constantly beheld your protective benevolence, and dare not let it slip from mind. Yet now I face one or two matters of humble concern that I dare not bring directly before the throne, and so I place my hope in your noble wisdom.

    Our small realm, having endured thirty years of warfare and pestilence, has seen our people and resources greatly depleted. We struggle to meet even our daily expenses and annual tributes. And now, as royal envoys arrive with requests stemming from troubles with the Eastern Barbarians and Western Song, they demand ten thousand soldiers and a thousand ships. Though our mountains may yield timber for shipbuilding, how can we suddenly produce a thousand vessels? Though we exhaust our rosters for conscription, how can we gather ten thousand capable fighters? Even should we somehow meet these numbers and venture across the great ocean to threaten distant lands, would not such ambitions invite equal peril upon ourselves? The resentment born from this would cut deep indeed. Thus, while we dare not show disrespect to the superior realm, such demands bring only ruin to our small nation. Most grievously, we fear we cannot even preserve our modest coastal territories. When I contemplate how this threatens the great virtue of the Emperor's gracious protection, my heart breaks with anguish.

    I humbly beseech Your Excellency to understand the hardship and danger of our distant position, and to have pity upon our state's desperate struggle for survival. May you employ your deep compassion and grand righteousness to calmly and clearly relay our petition to the throne, so that our small realm might be treated with mercy and clemency. The gratitude we would bear could never be fully expressed. I have now dispatched a humble envoy to the palace to offer New Year's felicitations and deliver this sealed letter. I only pray that in this new year, you and the imperial court will regard the realm with utmost care and consideration, and continue to shelter our small nation with enduring protection.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Silver Terrace' (銀臺) refers to the imperial court's administrative offices, and the addressee is likely a high-ranking Chinese official.
    - The references to 'Eastern Barbarians' (東倭) and 'Western Song' (西宋) likely refer to military threats or diplomatic pressures from neighboring powers.
    - The 'five blessings' (五福) in Chinese tradition are longevity, wealth, health, virtue, and a peaceful death.
    - The image of the 'scorpion's poison' (蠆毒) is used metaphorically to suggest that military ventures abroad invite reciprocal harm and enmity.
